@node Contents "Contents"

   This archive should contain the following files:

        NewFlash.dsrx             - A modified version of the flash effect
        NewFlashDemo.IFF          - Demo picture for flash effect
        NewFlashDemo.IFF.info     - Flash effect demo picture's icon
        Grid.dsrx                 - Draws a simple grid (useful for charts)
        GridDemo.IFF              - Demo picture for grid script
        GridDemo.IFF.info         - Grid demo picture's icon
        NewPie.dsrx               - Improved pie chart script
        NewPieDemo.IFF            - Demo picture for pie chart script
        NewPieDemo.IFF.info       - Pie chart demo picture's icon
        FontList.dsrx             - Hacky script to generate a font list
        FontListDemo.IFF          - Demo picture for font list script
        FontListDemo.IFF.info     - Font list demo picture's icon
        Spiral.dsrx               - Script to create a spiral
        Spiral.IFF                - Demo picture for spiral script
        Spiral.IFF.info           - Spiral demo picture's icon
        DSMiscRexxVol2.Guide      - This file
        DSMiscRexxVol2.Guide.info - This file's icon

   If for any reason it doesn't, this program can be downloaded from the
Aminet (or obtained from an Aminet CD) in the util/rexx directory as
DSMiscRexxVol2.lha.

@endnode

@node Brief "Brief description of the scripts"

The scripts are easily installed by simply selecting "All Files" from the
"Show" sub-menu in the "Window" menu on Workbench with the window
containing this document selected. Just drag all the files ending in .dsrx
over to the "Rexx" drawer in your DrawStudio folder or disc. It's that
easy! If, however you are already running DrawStudio, you'll have to wait
until the next time you load the program before you can use the scripts.

IMPORTANT! Some of these scripts require rexxmathlib.library (available
from Aminet sites at util/rexx/RexxMathLib.lha or on Aminet CD 16).
Additionally, you will also require a macro recorder/player program such
as Oliver Grimm's excellent Recorder (which you can get from Aminet
under util/cli/recorder.lha or from Aminet CD 13). Recorder is required
to work around some of the limitations in DrawStudio's otherwise
excellent and comprehensive ARexx command set.

Before you read about the scripts, why not have a quick peek at the demo
pictures I have included along with the scripts ? If English isn't your
first language, then you might find the pictures a little more helpful.
Anyway, this is what they do...

* NewFlash - This script is a modification of the original Flash script.
             The difference this time is that the flash effect
             alternates between two peak heights rather than just one.
             Take a look at the demo picture and compare it to the first
             implementation and you'll see what I'm getting at. I did
             have a slightly insane thought recently about modifying the
             script further to generate animation frames. Conceivably,
             this could produce a nice spinning star effect for web
             pages and so on. All we need now is a *decent* AnimGIF
             converter! Finally, this script like many similar ones that
             I have written has a limit to the number of verticies you can
             have. You can get away with about 83 in this case. This
             limitation comes from ARexx, not DrawStudio.

* NewPie -   This is a slight improvement upon my otherwise naff attempt at
             creating pie charts. Although I painstakingly tried to
             figure out how to generate an arc from bezier curves, the
             slightly more obvious solution of just joining a "real" arc
             to the other two sides of the slice made itself known. In
             fact, this script (along with most of the other scripts in
             this volume, actually) has been lying around on my hard
             drive for some time, so it's not a recent idea. Oh, and if
             you try out the script, you'll notice that it can do some
             cool things like allowing you to pick up individual slices and
             move them elsewhere. I have noticed that DrawStudio does
             tend to do some funny things like making slices disappear
             during generation. As far as I can tell, this is a bug in
             DrawStudio. The only work around I can come up with is to
             select all the slices using "Select All" from the menu, and
             manually re-colour, set the line style and thickness of all
             the objects first. It appears that in these cases
             DrawStudio fails to initialise the objects with any
             attributes, but it's easily fixed.

* FontList - I don't know about you, but I've yet to find a decent
             program for printing out previews of fonts. Since getting
             DrawStudio, I've pretty much chucked out my CompuGraphic
             fonts in favour of Adobe Type 1 fonts. I've got quite a
             sizable collection of them (primarily due to Amiga Format
             CDs, EMC Phase CDs, and of course the DrawStudio CD).
             However, it's a real chore picking the right font for the
             right occasion, so I like to have a printed copy of each
             font. By some strange coincidence, this script does just
             that. It takes DrawStudio's list of fonts, picks them out
             one by one and prints them on the page. Once the page is
             full, it creates a new page (in the same document) and
             proceeds until it's done all the fonts. Interestingly
             enough, DrawStudio deals with fonts quite efficiently, and
             so even with over 500 fonts, the memory didn't drop by more
             than a meg or so. I'd certainly recommend using DrawStudio
             over something like Wordworth, which despite being a fine
             program appears to have a slightly more inferior font
             engine and so some Type 1 fonts don't always appear,
             whereas pretty much all of the fonts I tried with
             DrawStudio worked a treat. Some fonts will of course play
             tricks with the font engine and the script will generate a
             log containing entries which do behave strangely. The way I
             detect "naughty" fonts is probably a bit unorthodox, but it
             seems to work OK. To accomodate such fonts into DrawStudio,
             get your hands on a copy of TypeSmith, load the font into
             it, and save it out again (using Adobe encoding, if I
             remember rightly). One final point: you'll need to get hold
             of a program such as "Recorder" from Aminet in order to use
             this script. To my knowledge, DrawStudio does not have the
             capability to add a new page to a document through ARexx
             (if someone knows differently, please get in touch so I can
             make this script slightly less hacky). Using Recorder, you
             must record your mouse movements from calling up the page
             requester and clicking "New", then clicking "OK". I haven't
             included my own version because everyone's display is set
             up differently, and while my file may work for some, it
             won't work for most other people.

* Grid -     Boring though it is, this script generates a grid of a
             specified size and number of cells (with the number of
             cells for accross and down being set individually). This
             sort of thing is primarily of use to people that want to
             produce tables, or guides for histograms (such as those
             produced by the bar graph script in the last volume). The
             demo picture is just an alternative use (in combination
             with the DrawStudio Warp function).

* Spiral -   It may come as a bit of a surprise but in actual fact this
             script draws a spiral shape. It's nothing particularly
             special as it stands, but the script can be tweaked to make
             the edges sharper to give a spiral polygon (experiment with
             the values, and you'll see). It's not likely to be one of
             the most useful scripts you'll ever get your hands on, but
             it can produce some interesting effects when you apply
             fills to it. I've noticed some problems with this script
             which I believe stem from bugs in DrawStudio. If you have
             another object selected on the page, the script doesn't
             finish drawing the spiral. I've no idea why. I've tried
             to work around it within the script, but it doesn't appear
             to help.

If you're quite handy with ARexx, you'll find that I've commented the code
as fully as I can so that it'll be easier for you to figure out what's
going on and tweak it if necessary.

@endnode

@node Distribution "Distribution"

    As with all the software I write, these scripts are FREEWARE. You
can distribute this archive where you like, provided the archive remains
complete and unmodified (I would appreciate being notified if they go on
a coverdisc or CD). You are also free to use these scripts as the basis
of any scripts of your own. If they're for DrawStudio, I'd be interested
to see what you create, although this is by no means essential.

@endnode

